    <!-- Page 3: Render + Introduction -->
    <section class="intro">
      <img src="assets/antarctica-thumbnail.jpg" alt="Antarctica Project Render" style="width: 80%; border-radius: 12px;" />
      <h3>Redesigning Maitri Station</h3>
      <p>
        The project proposes a reimagined version of India’s Maitri Antarctic Research Station, designed to endure extreme conditions while embracing sustainability and scientific ambition. The station floats 2–3m above the ground, sheltered within a 14m tall exoskeleton that reflects the undulating terrain of Antarctica.
      </p>
      <h3>Concept & Process</h3>
      <img src="assets/antarctica/quote.png" style="width: 100%; border-radius: 12px;"/>
      <p>
        The concept stems from the idea of a “second skin”—a protective exoskeleton that shelters the research modules from harsh wind, snow accumulation, and thermal loss. The form evolves through parametric design using Grasshopper, adapting to functional zoning, terrain contours, and solar orientation.
      </p>
      <p>
        Interior modules are suspended inside this exoskeleton, allowing wind to pass beneath and around, while maintaining thermal isolation. Modular clusters follow a programmatic spine: residential, laboratory, operations, and logistics, with utility cores strategically placed for maintenance efficiency.
      </p>
      <h3>Project Drawings</h3>
